Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

This page gives you guidance on how to stay safely in Serbia as a visitor, if you are unable to return to the UK.
Everyone should comply with the measures put in place in Serbia to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
Moving around in Serbia
For information on entering Serbia, see Entry Requirements
There is a ban on public gatherings of more than 20 people. Social distancing at all times is encouraged.
Public transport (including inter-city transport) is gradually restarting across the country, with public transport in Belgrade resuming on 8 May. Passengers will be required to wear protective facemasks and gloves.
Most businesses, shops, parks and public places are now able to open, with shopping malls reopening from 8 May. Restaurants and cafes with outdoor seating have also reopened.
Schools and universities remain closed until further notice. Some kindergartens and day care facilities will re-open from 11 May.
There may be further restrictions to limit the spread of coronavirus. Infringements of these procedures may result in fines and/or a prison sentence. If you are currently in Serbia, check news outlets regularly for up to date information.
If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Serbian Embassy or Consulate. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Visas
The right to remain in Serbia for foreign nationals was extended until the end of the State of Emergency (6 May). We are awaiting further guidance on visa status for affected foreign nationals.
